          <h2 style="             
              font-size: 20px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">Oil spill near Black Sea</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.presidentialsummary.com/email/images/ps-dec-17-2.jpg" alt="Oil spill near Black Sea" href="https://www.presidentialsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4; filter: blur(5px);">On Sunday, two Russian tankers, Volgoneft 212 and Volgoneft 239, were severely <a href="https://edition.cnn.com/2024/12/16/europe/russian-tankers-oil-spill-black-sea-intl/index.html" target="_blank">damaged</a> during a storm near the Kerch Strait, spilling oil into the Black Sea. Winds reached 45 mph (70 kph), causing one ship to split in two, with water flooding its deck. The Volgoneft 212 <a href="https://tass.com/emergencies/1887747" target="_blank">lost</a> its bow, and one crew member died. The Volgoneft 239 ran aground near Taman in Russia’s Krasnodar region, with 14 crew members rescued. The vessels carried approximately 8000 tons of oil, and over 4300 tons spilled into the sea, according to Greenpeace.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4; filter: blur(5px);">
          Greenpeace <a href="https://www.greenpeace.org/ukraine/en/novyny/3135/russian-militarisation-of-the-black-sea-and-azov-threatens-with-new-environmental-catastrophe/" target="_blank">expressed</a> concern that the spill could have severe environmental impacts, mainly if it involved heavy fuel oils. Dr Paul Johnson, head of Greenpeace Research Laboratories, said if the ships sink, the potential for more petrochemicals over a longer period of time is higher. This incident brings back <a href="https://www.unep.org/ukraine" target="_blank">memories</a> of a similar spill in 2007 in the same region.</p>
        </mj-text>
